1
00:00:00,050 --> 00:00:05,516
You're listening to: Database Connection Pooling: The Performance Fix That Saved Our Production.

2
00:00:05,516 --> 00:00:10,973
How I learned about connection pooling after our PostgreSQL database crashed under load.

3
00:00:10,973 --> 00:00:16,550
Practical guide with real configurations from handling millions of healthcare queries.

4
00:00:16,550 --> 00:00:17,608
Let's get started.

5
00:00:17,608 --> 00:00:20,889
Now, let's talk about The Monday Morning That Changed Everything.

6
00:00:20,889 --> 00:00:22,656
It was 9:15 AM.

7
00:00:22,656 --> 00:00:31,622
Our busiest time - patients arriving for their morning appointments, doctors pulling up test results, lab techs entering data from overnight samples.

8
00:00:31,622 --> 00:00:33,137
Then everything stopped.

9
00:00:33,137 --> 00:00:36,502
PostgreSQL had hit max_connections.

10
00:00:36,502 --> 00:00:44,074
Our app had 3 instances, each opening 50 connections, but PostgreSQL was configured for 100 max.

11
00:00:44,074 --> 00:00:49,471
We were at 150 attempted connections and the database was refusing new ones.

12
00:00:49,471 --> 00:00:51,201
Error logs filled with:

13
00:00:51,201 --> 00:00:53,329
Patients couldn't see their reports.

14
00:00:53,329 --> 00:00:55,444
Doctors couldn't access histories.

15
00:00:55,444 --> 00:00:57,439
Sample tracking went dark.

16
00:00:57,439 --> 00:01:02,608
We scrambled to restart services, but they'd immediately exhaust connections again.

17
00:01:02,608 --> 00:01:08,377
The only fix was killing application instances one by one until we got back under the limit.

18
00:01:08,377 --> 00:01:13,173
That day cost us 47 minutes of downtime and a lot of angry phone calls.

19
00:01:13,173 --> 00:01:17,163
It also taught me everything I now know about connection pooling.

20
00:01:17,163 --> 00:01:21,105
Moving on to Why This Happens (And Why I Didn't See It Coming).

21
00:01:21,105 --> 00:01:24,002
I'd always thought "just add more connections" was the answer.

22
00:01:24,002 --> 00:01:28,798
More connections = more queries = better performance, right?

23
00:01:28,798 --> 00:01:29,963
Completely wrong.

24
00:01:29,963 --> 00:01:31,887
Here's what was happening in our system:

25
00:01:31,887 --> 00:01:34,543
Next up: The Fix: Connection Pooling.

26
00:01:34,543 --> 00:01:38,353
After that incident, I spent a week understanding connection pooling.

27
00:01:38,353 --> 00:01:39,927
The concept is simple:

28
00:01:39,927 --> 00:01:46,189
Instead of each request opening a new connection, requests borrow from a pool and return when done.

29
00:01:46,189 --> 00:01:49,975
The pool maintains a fixed number of actual database connections.

30
00:01:49,975 --> 00:01:52,223
Let's explore What I Actually Implemented.

31
00:01:52,223 --> 00:01:54,939
Application-Level Pooling with asyncpg.

32
00:01:54,939 --> 00:01:59,699
For our FastAPI services, I used asyncpg with a properly configured pool:

33
00:01:59,699 --> 00:02:02,403
The Pool Sizing Formula That Actually Works.

34
00:02:02,403 --> 00:02:05,961
I spent way too long trying different pool sizes.

35
00:02:05,961 --> 00:02:07,872
Here's the formula I settled on:

36
00:02:07,872 --> 00:02:11,225
I tried 50 connections once thinking "more is better."

37
00:02:11,225 --> 00:02:13,906
The database got slower, not faster.

38
00:02:13,906 --> 00:02:19,747
Too many connections means PostgreSQL spends more time scheduling processes than running queries.

39
00:02:19,747 --> 00:02:21,646
FastAPI Integration.

40
00:02:21,646 --> 00:02:24,302
Here's how we wire it up in FastAPI:

41
00:02:24,302 --> 00:02:28,882
Now let's look at PgBouncer: When Application Pooling Isn't Enough.

42
00:02:28,882 --> 00:02:31,430
After a few months, we hit another problem.

43
00:02:31,430 --> 00:02:36,105
We had 5 application instances, each with a pool of 20 connections.

44
00:02:36,105 --> 00:02:40,492
That's 100 connections to PostgreSQL - right at our limit again.

45
00:02:40,492 --> 00:02:46,418
Enter PgBouncer - a connection pooler that sits between your applications and PostgreSQL.

46
00:02:46,418 --> 00:02:48,617
My PgBouncer Configuration.

47
00:02:48,617 --> 00:02:52,584
The pool_mode = transaction setting is crucial.

48
00:02:52,584 --> 00:02:59,110
It means connections are returned to the pool after each transaction completes, not when the client disconnects.

49
00:02:59,110 --> 00:03:02,283
This dramatically improves connection reuse.

50
00:03:02,283 --> 00:03:04,483
Running PgBouncer in Docker.

51
00:03:04,483 --> 00:03:09,663
Now, let's talk about Monitoring: How I Catch Problems Before They Crash Production.

52
00:03:09,663 --> 00:03:14,098
After the Monday incident, I added monitoring for everything pool-related:

53
00:03:14,098 --> 00:03:15,324
Alerts I Have Set Up.

54
00:03:15,324 --> 00:03:18,413
Moving on to Common Mistakes I Made (So You Don't Have To).

55
00:03:18,413 --> 00:03:20,949
Mistake 1: Pool Too Large.

56
00:03:20,949 --> 00:03:22,091
Bigger isn't better.

57
00:03:22,091 --> 00:03:28,533
200 connections to PostgreSQL means 200 processes competing for resources.

58
00:03:28,533 --> 00:03:31,814
Mistake 2: Forgetting to Release Connections.

59
00:03:31,814 --> 00:03:35,576
Mistake 3: Holding Connections During Slow Operations.

60
00:03:35,576 --> 00:03:39,074
The first version holds a connection for 2+ seconds.

61
00:03:39,074 --> 00:03:41,911
The second version holds it for milliseconds.

62
00:03:41,911 --> 00:03:43,810
Next up: The Results.

63
00:03:43,810 --> 00:03:46,526
After implementing proper connection pooling:

64
00:03:46,526 --> 00:03:48,269
Metric, Before, After.

65
00:03:48,269 --> 00:03:54,110
Max PostgreSQL connections, 100 → always hitting limit, 30 → plenty of headroom.

66
00:03:54,110 --> 00:03:58,281
Connection errors, 50-100/day, 0.

67
00:03:58,281 --> 00:04:04,411
Query latency p99, 800ms, 45ms.

68
00:04:04,411 --> 00:04:07,668
App instances supported, 2, 10+.

69
00:04:07,668 --> 00:04:10,697
The 47-minute outage never happened again.

70
00:04:10,697 --> 00:04:17,367
And when traffic spikes, instead of crashing, we just queue requests briefly while waiting for connections.

71
00:04:17,367 --> 00:04:19,915
Let's explore My Checklist for New Projects.

72
00:04:19,898 --> 00:04:27,155
Connection pooling isn't glamorous, but it's the difference between a system that scales and one that falls over under load.

73
00:04:27,155 --> 00:04:29,739
I learned this the hard way so you don't have to.

74
00:04:29,739 --> 00:04:33,958
The patterns here have handled millions of queries per day in production.

75
00:04:33,958 --> 00:04:35,701
They'll probably handle yours too.

